The image is a line graph that compares memory usage between two methods: "Ours" (blue line with circular markers) and "Traditional" (red line with x markers), with respect to the number of transparent objects. The x-axis represents the "Number of transparent objects" (1, 2, 4, 8), and the y-axis represents "Required memory (Megabytes)" (ranging from 0 to 36). The "Ours" method maintains a constant memory usage of around 9 megabytes regardless of the number of transparent objects, while the "Traditional" method increases linearly from about 4.5 megabytes at 1 transparent object to approximately 35.5 megabytes at 8 transparent objects. A legend is included to distinguish between the two methods. Here's the LaTeX code using the pgfplots package to generate this graph:

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}

\usepackage{pgfplots}
\usepgfplotslibrary{groupplots}
\pgfplotsset{compat=1.17} % Adjust compat value as needed

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}
    \begin{axis}[
        xlabel={Number of transparent objects},
        ylabel={Required memory (Megabytes)},
        xmin=0.5, xmax=8.5,
        ymin=0, ymax=36,
        xtick={1,2,4,8},
        ytick={2,4,...,36},
        grid=both,
        grid style={line width=.1pt, draw=gray!30},
        major grid style={line width=.2pt,draw=gray!50},
        legend pos=north west,
        legend cell align={left},
        legend style={draw=none},
        mark size=3pt,
        ]
        \addplot[
            color=blue,
            mark=*,
            every mark/.append style={solid},
            ] coordinates {
                (1,4.5) (2,9) (4,9) (8,9)
            };
        \addlegendentry{Ours}
        \addplot[
            color=red,
            mark=x,
            every mark/.append style={solid},
            ] coordinates {
                (1,4.5) (2,9.1) (4,18) (8,35.5)
            };
        \addlegendentry{Traditional}
    \end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

This code sets up a standalone TikZ document with the pgfplots package, configuring the axes and grid lines to match the image. It plots two lines: one for "Ours" and one for "Traditional," with the appropriate markers and colors, and includes a legend to label each line. The memory usage values for each method at different numbers of transparent objects are specified in the `coordinates` for each `\addplot` command.

